PR-ST-01 — Start launch-gating for static-route-capable bundles
Title

Add static-route capability detection and launch compatibility checks to greentic-start

Goal

Before booting runtime services, greentic-start should determine whether the selected bundle contains static routes and whether the chosen startup mode supports hosting them.

Why

start already owns:

bundle resolution

config resolution

runtime mode selection

tunnel/public URL resolution

service launch

So it should also own:

launch compatibility for static hosting

Scope
Detect static-route declarations

Extend startup inspection so it scans bundled pack manifests for:

greentic.static-routes.v1

Use the same direct pack-manifest inspection pattern already used for capabilities/offers.

Compute startup compatibility

Before launching runtime, determine:

whether any selected pack declares static routes

whether public HTTP is enabled in this launch mode

whether asset serving is supported

whether a resolved public_base_url exists when required

Startup behavior

if no static routes are declared: no behavior change

if static routes are declared and runtime mode supports them: continue

if static routes are declared but mode is incompatible: fail early with a clear message

Resolved handoff

Pass a small resolved startup contract into runtime/operator, for example through env and/or startup metadata:

PUBLIC_HTTP_ENABLED

STATIC_ROUTES_ENABLED

ASSET_SERVING_ENABLED

PUBLIC_BASE_URL

maybe a summarized “bundle has static routes” flag

Do not do here

no route serving

no full static-route schema validation

no runtime collision detection

no pack schema authorship

Files likely touched

startup capability inspection

launch validation path

runtime env handoff

startup metadata persistence

docs for startup mode compatibility

Acceptance criteria

start can detect bundles that declare static routes

incompatible launch modes fail before runtime starts

resolved launch contract is passed to operator/runtime

no route-serving logic is added to start